{{BLP primary sources|date=March 2013}} :''For the creator of the TV series [[Desperate Housewives]], see [[Marc Cherry]]''. '''Mark J. Cherry''' is the Dr. Patricia A. Hayes Professor in Applied Ethics at [[St. Edward's University]], Austin, Texas.<ref name=bio><nowiki>[http://www.asiaing.com/prohibitions-by-the-institute-of-economic-affairs.html Mark J. Cherry]</nowiki>, Asiaing.com, accessed January 23, 2010.</ref> He is the author of ''Kidney for Sale by Owner: Human Organs, Transplantation, and the Market'' (2005), in which he argues that human body parts are commodities, and that the market is the most efficient and morally justified way to procure and allocate organs for transplant. His argument is based in part on what he calls the [[moral authority]] of persons over themselves.<ref>Cherry, Mark. [http://jmp.oxfordjournals.org/cgi/content/short/jhp048v1 "Why Should We Compensate Organ Donors When We Can Continue to Take Organs for Free? A Response to Some of My Critics"], ''The Journal of Medicine and Philosophy'', October 21, 2009.</ref> Cherry is the editor of the ''Journal of Medicine and Philosophy'', ''Christian Bioethics'', editor-in-chief of the Health- Care Ethics Committee Forum, and series co-editor of the ''Annals of Bioethics''.<ref name=bio/> __TOC__
